---
// The thesis, as a short editorial passage. Positions Pulse against the apps
// people already use before any feature is named.
---
<section class="px-6 py-24 md:py-32" aria-labelledby="promise-heading">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-[52rem] text-center" data-reveal>
    <p class="font-mono text-[var(--pulse-accent-strong)] mb-6 text-[0.72rem] tracking-[0.28em] uppercase">
      Why Pulse
    </p>
    <h2
      id="promise-heading"
      class="font-display text-[var(--color-text)] text-[clamp(1.9rem,4.5vw,3rem)] leading-[1.2]"
    >
      All the good parts, none of the <span class="italic text-[var(--pulse-accent)]">FOMO</span>.
    </h2>
    <p class="font-body text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mx-auto mt-7 max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8]">
      Facebook Events knows who&rsquo;s going but feels like 2012. Partiful and Luma are fun to host
      with but stop at your own invites. Eventbrite has the tooling and the soul of a tax form.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-[var(--color-text)] mt-6 mx-auto max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8]">
      Pulse is the one that does all three: the social ease of knowing your friends are out, the joy
      of a beautiful invite, and real organiser tooling underneath. Open it and the default question
      is already answered — <em class="not-italic font-semibold">what&rsquo;s happening today, near me?</em>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
